nodes.title: Groups Bypasser Note
widgets_values:
This node controls which groups are enabled by default. I recommend:
- Enable Initial Gen

Once you find a prompt you like, then 
- Enable Upscale


If you want to preview steps between generations (say to test out the impacts of upscaling), you can enable the [PREVIEW] sections.

Enable Style Transfer and Controlnet Depth to use those features.

If you're testing out new styles and want quick generations, just enable "Enable Initial Gen"
with nothing else. That will give you a quick way to test then you can enable the more costly upscale nodes.

nodes.title: Usage Notes
widgets_values:
======== PROMPTING ========
If you're new to prompting pony models, you need to know about danbooru tags:
https://danbooru.donmai.us/wiki_pages/tag_groups

Pony was trained on these tags, so knowing the exact words to propmt can be very helpful.

Weighting your propmts also helps a lot. If you want something expressed more, turn up the weight! For example, try changing (__f/color__ theme:1.1), in the prompt to (__f/color__ theme:1.5),

========   STYLE   ========
You may notice that my images use higher CFG than normal images. That is thanks to Skimmed CFG:
https://github.com/Extraltodeus/Skimmed_CFG

It allows you to turn up CFG without making them a pixelated, burned mess. Each model treats CFG differently. Pony models are generally fine around 5/12/24 CFG, but SDXL may require less. Experiment with these values and see what matches your preferred style!

======== WILDCARDS ========
Open the included wildcards file to see how you can introduce controlled randomness to your generations. Docs here: https://github.com/ltdrdata/ComfyUI-extension-tutorials/blob/Main/ComfyUI-Impact-Pack/tutorial/ImpactWildcard.md

In the prompt, you see syntax like: __f/scene/modeling-clothed__. This refers to the wildcard yaml file by key. Look at f (the top level key in the file), then search for scene which will be one indentation deeper, then modeling-clothed which is another indentation under that. List items are chosen at random. This can be useful if you want to try out different hair styles/ clothes/ backgrounds/ etc.

If you're not familiar with yaml files, I suggest downloading VSCode for syntax highlighting.

If you're modifying wildcards, you must refresh them before they work. In the top menu, select "Edit" > "Impact: Refresh Wildcards"

========   LORAS   ========
In the "Positive WildcardEncode" section you can add loras by clicking the "Select to add LoRA" widget at the bottom. That will append the LoRA tag at the bottom of the prompt like:
<lora:loraname>

You can change the strength of a LoRA like:
<lora:loraname:0.8>

If you don't see your lora, you may need to refresh. Press "r" and that will refresh ComfyUI's node values.

As a note, you can embed this lora syntax in wildcard files as well, so if you capture a style you like, you can "save" it by using a wildcard that you reference later. Search for the commented out "bodylora:" section in the included wildcards for an example.

nodes.title: Example Prompting with Wildcards
widgets_values:
# Example wildcard usage:
# Paste this into the Positive WildcardEncode block

# NOTE: Include a "# " at the beginning of a line to comment it out. Notice that this line doesn't appear in the output on the left! This can be useful when testing new prompt ideas.

score_9, score_8_up, score_7_up,

({cute|beautiful} face,:1.2)
__f/person/rando__,
__f/body/*__,

__f/scene/modeling-clothed__,

(__f/color__ theme:1.1), vivid colors,

masterpiece, realistic, raw photo, cinematic, analog, 8k, depth of field, 
best quality, highres, shot on Canon EOS 5D.
